tables.description: The audit_checks table represents a record of regular audits performed across various sites. It stores information about the audit date, the auditor, and the audit score. This table is typically used in analytics and business workflows to track compliance and identify areas for improvement.

columns.description: The audit_pk column represents a unique identifier for each audit record, serving as a primary key. It stores an integer value, which is used to uniquely identify each audit entry. This column is crucial for data integrity and facilitates efficient querying and analysis of audit data.

The site_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the site_master table, linking each audit record to the corresponding site. It stores an integer value, which is used to establish the relationship between audits and sites. This column enables the analysis of audit data in the context of specific sites.

The audit_dt column represents the date on which the audit was performed. It stores a date value, which is used to track the timing of audits. This column is essential for understanding the frequency and timing of audits, enabling informed decisions about audit schedules and resource allocation.

The auditor column represents the individual who performed the audit. It stores a character varying value, which is used to record the auditor's name. This column is crucial for tracking audit responsibilities and ensuring accountability.

The audit_score column represents the score obtained during the audit. It stores an integer value, which is used to evaluate the audit outcome. This column is essential for assessing compliance and identifying areas for improvement.

tables.description: The event_log table captures significant events that occur within the organization, including staff activities and system events. It stores information about the event date, category, and risk level. This table is crucial for auditing and monitoring purposes, helping to identify potential security threats and areas for process improvement.

columns.description: The event_pk column represents a unique identifier for each event record, serving as a primary key. It stores an integer value, which is used to uniquely identify each event entry. This column is crucial for data integrity and facilitates efficient querying and analysis of event data.

The staff_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the staff table, linking each event record to the corresponding staff member. It stores an integer value, which is used to establish the relationship between events and staff. This column enables the analysis of event data in the context of specific staff members.

The event_dt column represents the date on which the event occurred. It stores a date value, which is used to track the timing of events. This column is essential for understanding the frequency and timing of events, enabling informed decisions about event schedules and resource allocation.

The event_category column represents the category of the event. It stores a character varying value, which is used to classify events. This column is crucial for understanding the nature of events and identifying patterns and trends.

The risk_level column represents the level of risk associated with the event. It stores an integer value, which is used to evaluate the severity of the event. This column is essential for assessing potential threats and identifying areas for mitigation.

tables.description: The learning_records table stores information about staff training and development activities. It records the course name, completion status, and the date the course was taken. This table is essential for tracking staff skills and knowledge, enabling informed decisions about training and development programs.

columns.description: The learning_pk column represents a unique identifier for each learning record, serving as a primary key. It stores an integer value, which is used to uniquely identify each learning entry. This column is crucial for data integrity and facilitates efficient querying and analysis of learning data.

The staff_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the staff table, linking each learning record to the corresponding staff member. It stores an integer value, which is used to establish the relationship between learning records and staff. This column enables the analysis of learning data in the context of specific staff members.

The course_name column represents the name of the course taken by the staff member. It stores a character varying value, which is used to record the course title. This column is essential for tracking staff training and development activities.

The course_dt column represents the date on which the course was taken. It stores a date value, which is used to track the timing of courses. This column is crucial for understanding the frequency and timing of courses, enabling informed decisions about training and development programs.

The completion_status column represents the status of the course completion. It stores a character varying value, which is used to record the completion outcome. This column is essential for tracking staff learning outcomes and identifying areas for improvement.

tables.description: The org_units table represents the organizational structure of the company, including departments, teams, and units. It stores information about the unit title, site affiliation, and unit head. This table is vital for understanding the company's hierarchy and facilitating communication and collaboration across different units.

columns.description: The unit_pk column represents a unique identifier for each organizational unit, serving as a primary key. It stores an integer value, which is used to uniquely identify each unit entry. This column is crucial for data integrity and facilitates efficient querying and analysis of unit data.

The unit_title column represents the title of the organizational unit. It stores a character varying value, which is used to record the unit name. This column is essential for understanding the company's hierarchy and facilitating communication and collaboration across different units.

The site_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the site_master table, linking each unit record to the corresponding site. It stores an integer value, which is used to establish the relationship between units and sites. This column enables the analysis of unit data in the context of specific sites.

The unit_head column represents the head of the organizational unit. It stores a character varying value, which is used to record the unit head's name. This column is crucial for understanding the company's hierarchy and facilitating communication and collaboration across different units.

The created_on column represents the date on which the unit was created. It stores a timestamp value, which is used to track the timing of unit creation. This column is essential for understanding the history of unit changes and identifying areas for improvement.

tables.description: The site_master table stores information about company sites, including their titles, locations, and creation dates. It provides a centralized repository for site-related data, enabling easy management and analysis of site performance and operations.

columns.description: The site_pk column represents a unique identifier for each site, serving as a primary key. It stores an integer value, which is used to uniquely identify each site entry. This column is crucial for data integrity and facilitates efficient querying and analysis of site data.

The site_title column represents the title of the site. It stores a character varying value, which is used to record the site name. This column is essential for understanding the company's sites and facilitating communication and collaboration across different locations.

The nation column represents the nation where the site is located. It stores a character varying value, which is used to record the site's location. This column is crucial for understanding the company's global presence and facilitating international collaboration.

The region column represents the region where the site is located. It stores a character varying value, which is used to record the site's location. This column is essential for understanding the company's regional presence and facilitating local collaboration.

The created_on column represents the date on which the site was created. It stores a timestamp value, which is used to track the timing of site creation. This column is crucial for understanding the history of site changes and identifying areas for improvement.

tables.description: The staff table represents the company's workforce, storing information about staff members, including their full names, roles, and joining dates. This table is essential for HR management, enabling the tracking of staff demographics, skills, and career development.

columns.description: The staff_pk column represents a unique identifier for each staff member, serving as a primary key. It stores an integer value, which is used to uniquely identify each staff entry. This column is crucial for data integrity and facilitates efficient querying and analysis of staff data.

The staff_fullname column represents the full name of the staff member. It stores a character varying value, which is used to record the staff member's name. This column is essential for understanding the company's workforce and facilitating communication and collaboration across different teams.

The unit_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the org_units table, linking each staff record to the corresponding unit. It stores an integer value, which is used to establish the relationship between staff and units. This column enables the analysis of staff data in the context of specific units.

The role_name column represents the role of the staff member. It stores a character varying value, which is used to record the staff member's role. This column is crucial for understanding the company's organizational structure and facilitating communication and collaboration across different teams.

The joining_date column represents the date on which the staff member joined the company. It stores a date value, which is used to track the timing of staff joining. This column is essential for understanding the company's workforce dynamics and facilitating informed decisions about staffing and resource allocation.
